{
  "Which of the following is considered a renewable energy source?": "",
  "Natural gas": "",
  "Petroleum": "",
  "Coal": "",
  "Solar energy": "",
  "Solar energy is renewable because it is naturally replenished on a human timescale. The Sun continuously provides energy, unlike coal, natural gas, and petroleum, which take millions of years to form.": "",
  "What type of energy conversion occurs in a solar photovoltaic cell?": "",
  "Heat energy to mechanical energy": "",
  "Nuclear energy to thermal energy": "",
  "Chemical energy to light energy": "",
  "Light energy to electrical energy": "",
  "Solar photovoltaic cells convert light energy directly into electrical energy through the photovoltaic effect, where photons striking semiconductor material cause electrons to flow and generate an electric current.": "",
  "Which part of a wind turbine converts kinetic energy into electrical energy?": "",
  "The blades": "",
  "The foundation": "",
  "The nacelle's generator": "",
  "The tower": "",
  "The generator housed inside the nacelle is the component that converts the rotational kinetic energy of the spinning shaft into electrical energy. The blades capture wind energy and turn the shaft, but the generator performs the actual energy conversion.": "",
  "What is the primary energy source that drives the water cycle, making hydroelectric power possible?": "",
  "The Sun": "",
  "The Moon's gravity": "",
  "Geothermal heat": "",
  "Earth's rotation": "",
  "The Sun drives the water cycle by providing the heat energy needed to evaporate water from oceans, lakes, and rivers. This evaporated water eventually falls as precipitation, filling reservoirs and rivers that hydroelectric dams use to generate electricity.": "",
  "What material is most commonly used in solar photovoltaic cells?": "",
  "Iron": "",
  "Silicon": "",
  "Copper": "",
  "Aluminum": "",
  "Silicon is the most commonly used semiconductor material in photovoltaic cells. It is abundant in Earth's crust and has ideal electronic properties for converting sunlight into electricity through the photovoltaic effect.": "",
  "What is the main advantage of hydroelectric power compared to fossil fuels?": "",
  "It has no impact on aquatic ecosystems": "",
  "It produces no greenhouse gas emissions during operation": "",
  "It requires less initial investment": "",
  "It can be built anywhere regardless of geography": "",
  "Hydroelectric power produces no greenhouse gas emissions during electricity generation, unlike fossil fuels which release carbon dioxide and other pollutants when burned. However, dam construction and reservoir flooding can have ecological impacts.": "",
  "Which renewable energy source depends on differences in atmospheric pressure caused by uneven heating of Earth's surface?": "",
  "Tidal energy": "",
  "Geothermal energy": "",
  "Wind energy": "",
  "Biomass energy": "",
  "Wind is created by uneven heating of Earth's surface by the Sun, which causes differences in atmospheric pressure. Air flows from high-pressure areas to low-pressure areas, creating wind that can be harnessed by turbines.": "",
  "What type of hydroelectric system does not require a large dam or reservoir?": "",
  "Tidal barrage hydropower": "",
  "Pumped-storage hydropower": "",
  "Conventional dam hydropower": "",
  "Run-of-river hydropower": "",
  "Run-of-river hydropower systems divert a portion of a river's flow through turbines without requiring a large dam or reservoir. This approach has a smaller environmental footprint but depends on consistent river flow rates.": "",
  "What is the approximate efficiency of most commercial silicon solar panels?": "",
  "5-10%": "",
  "80-90%": "",
  "50-60%": "",
  "15-22%": "",
  "Most commercial silicon solar panels have an efficiency of approximately 15-22%, meaning they convert that percentage of incoming sunlight into usable electricity. Research-grade panels can achieve higher efficiencies, but commercial panels remain in this range due to cost constraints.": "",
  "Which country leads the world in total installed hydroelectric capacity?": "",
  "United States": "",
  "Brazil": "",
  "Norway": "",
  "China": "",
  "China leads the world in total installed hydroelectric capacity, with major projects including the Three Gorges Dam, the largest hydroelectric power station in the world by installed capacity. China has invested heavily in hydropower as part of its energy infrastructure.": "",
  "What is a renewable resource?": "",
  "A natural resource that is replenished on a human timescale through natural processes": "",
  "Any resource that can be recycled after use": "",
  "A resource that exists in unlimited quantities underground": "",
  "A resource that never runs out regardless of usage rate": "",
  "A renewable resource is a natural resource that can be replenished through natural processes on a human timescale. Examples include solar energy, wind, and water, which are continuously available unlike fossil fuels that take millions of years to form.": "",
  "What is the photovoltaic effect?": "",
  "The process of converting heat into mechanical energy": "",
  "The reflection of sunlight by mirrors to a central tower": "",
  "The generation of voltage and electric current when a material is exposed to light": "",
  "The warming of water in solar thermal collectors": "",
  "The photovoltaic effect is the physical phenomenon in which light striking a semiconductor material generates voltage and electric current. This effect is the fundamental principle behind solar photovoltaic cells that convert sunlight directly into electricity.": "",
  "What is a solar farm?": "",
  "A research laboratory studying the Sun": "",
  "A farm that grows crops using only solar-powered irrigation": "",
  "A large-scale installation of solar panels designed to generate electricity for the power grid": "",
  "A greenhouse heated by solar thermal collectors": "",
  "A solar farm is a large-scale installation consisting of many solar panels arranged over a wide area, designed to generate significant amounts of electricity that is fed into the power grid. Solar farms can cover hundreds of acres and power thousands of homes.": "",
  "What is capacity factor in the context of renewable energy?": "",
  "The total number of turbines or panels in an installation": "",
  "The percentage of land area covered by energy equipment": "",
  "The maximum amount of energy a power plant can store": "",
  "The ratio of actual energy output to maximum possible output over a period of time": "",
  "Capacity factor is the ratio of a power plant's actual energy output over a period of time to its maximum possible output if it operated at full capacity continuously. Wind turbines typically have capacity factors of 25-45%, while solar panels range from 15-25% depending on location.": "",
  "What is intermittency in renewable energy?": "",
  "The scheduled maintenance downtime of power plants": "",
  "The gradual decrease in energy output as equipment ages": "",
  "The variability in power generation due to fluctuating natural conditions like weather and daylight": "",
  "The inability to store excess energy for later use": "",
  "Intermittency refers to the inherent variability in power generation from renewable sources caused by changing natural conditions. Solar panels produce no electricity at night, and wind turbines cannot generate power during calm periods, creating challenges for grid reliability.": "",
  "What is a wind farm?": "",
  "A single large wind turbine used for research purposes": "",
  "An agricultural area that uses wind for irrigation pumps": "",
  "A collection of wind turbines in the same location used to produce electricity": "",
  "A factory where wind turbines are manufactured": "",
  "A wind farm is a group of wind turbines installed in the same area and connected to the electrical grid to generate electricity on a commercial scale. Wind farms can be located onshore or offshore and may contain dozens to hundreds of individual turbines.": "",
  "What is pumped-storage hydropower?": "",
  "A desalination plant powered by hydroelectricity": "",
  "A system that uses pumps to extract groundwater for hydroelectric generation": "",
  "A system that pumps water through turbines in a closed loop": "",
  "A method of storing energy by pumping water to a higher reservoir during low demand and releasing it to generate electricity during high demand": "",
  "Pumped-storage hydropower is a form of energy storage where water is pumped from a lower reservoir to an upper reservoir during periods of low electricity demand, then released back down through turbines to generate electricity when demand is high. It acts like a giant rechargeable battery for the grid.": "",
  "What is net metering?": "",
  "A system for tracking electricity consumption in real time": "",
  "A technique for calculating the carbon footprint of renewable energy": "",
  "A billing arrangement that credits solar panel owners for excess electricity they send back to the grid": "",
  "A method of measuring the total energy output of a power plant": "",
  "Net metering is a billing mechanism that credits owners of solar panels or other renewable energy systems for the surplus electricity they generate and feed back into the public grid. Their electric meter effectively runs backward when they produce more than they consume.": "",
  "What is concentrated solar power (CSP)?": "",
  "A technology that uses mirrors or lenses to focus sunlight onto a receiver to generate heat for electricity production": "",
  "An extremely high-efficiency photovoltaic cell used in space": "",
  "A type of solar cell that uses concentrated chemical solutions": "",
  "Solar panels arranged in a highly compact configuration on rooftops": "",
  "Concentrated solar power uses mirrors or lenses to concentrate a large area of sunlight onto a small receiver, generating intense heat that produces steam to drive a turbine and generate electricity. Unlike photovoltaic panels, CSP uses thermal energy rather than the photovoltaic effect.": "",
  "What is an inverter in a solar energy system?": "",
  "A component that tracks the Sun's position across the sky": "",
  "A device that stores excess solar energy in batteries": "",
  "A device that tilts solar panels to optimal angles": "",
  "A device that converts direct current (DC) from solar panels into alternating current (AC) for use in homes and the grid": "",
  "An inverter is a critical component in solar energy systems that converts the direct current (DC) electricity produced by solar panels into alternating current (AC) electricity, which is the standard form of electricity used in homes, businesses, and the electrical grid.": "",
  "A coastal community is considering building an offshore wind farm to replace an aging coal plant. However, local fishermen worry about impacts on marine life. Which of the following is the most accurate statement about offshore wind farms and marine ecosystems?": "",
  "Offshore wind farms permanently eliminate all fish populations in the surrounding area": "",
  "Offshore wind turbines have zero impact on marine ecosystems": "",
  "Marine life is only affected during the first week of construction": "",
  "Turbine foundations can act as artificial reefs, attracting marine life, though construction noise may temporarily disturb marine mammals": "",
  "Research has shown that offshore wind turbine foundations often become artificial reefs that attract fish, mussels, and other marine organisms. However, the noise from pile-driving during construction can temporarily disturb marine mammals such as dolphins and whales, requiring mitigation measures.": "",
  "A homeowner in Phoenix, Arizona installs a 6 kW solar panel system on their roof. During summer months, the system generates more electricity than the household uses during the day but none at night. What solution would best address the mismatch between energy production and consumption?": "",
  "Installing a larger solar panel system": "",
  "Adding a battery storage system or participating in net metering": "",
  "Using electricity only during daylight hours": "",
  "Switching to wind power at night": "",
  "Battery storage systems can store excess solar electricity generated during the day for use at night. Alternatively, net metering allows the homeowner to send surplus electricity to the grid during the day and draw from the grid at night, receiving credits for their exported power.": "",
  "A city planner is evaluating whether to build a hydroelectric dam on a major river. Environmental scientists warn that the dam could block salmon migration routes. Which of the following mitigation strategies is specifically designed to address fish migration concerns at dams?": "",
  "Releasing water only during non-migration seasons": "",
  "Building the dam higher to create a deeper reservoir": "",
  "Removing all vegetation along the riverbanks": "",
  "Installing fish ladders or fish passage structures": "",
  "Fish ladders are specially designed structures that allow fish to migrate upstream past a dam by providing a series of stepped pools that fish can jump through. Many modern dams incorporate fish passage structures to mitigate the impact on migratory species like salmon.": "",
  "A rural village in sub-Saharan Africa has no connection to a national power grid. The village receives abundant sunshine year-round and has limited financial resources. Which renewable energy approach would be most practical for providing electricity to individual homes?": "",
  "Installing small-scale solar home systems with batteries": "",
  "Constructing an offshore wind farm": "",
  "Connecting to a distant geothermal power plant": "",
  "Building a large hydroelectric dam nearby": "",
  "Small-scale solar home systems with batteries are ideal for off-grid communities in sunny regions because they are modular, relatively affordable, require minimal infrastructure, and can be installed on individual homes without the need for expensive grid connections or large-scale construction projects.": "",
  "A wind energy company is selecting a site for a new wind farm. They have narrowed their choices to four locations. Which site characteristic would be most important for maximizing energy production?": "",
  "A location in a deep valley surrounded by mountains": "",
  "A flat, open area with consistent high average wind speeds": "",
  "A densely forested area near a city": "",
  "A location with the warmest average temperatures": "",
  "Wind turbines produce the most energy in locations with consistent, high average wind speeds and minimal obstructions. Flat, open areas such as plains, ridgelines, and coastal regions provide the best conditions because there are no barriers to slow or disrupt wind flow.": "",
  "During a severe drought, a region that relies on hydroelectric power for 70% of its electricity experiences a significant drop in reservoir levels. Power officials warn of potential rolling blackouts. What does this scenario illustrate about renewable energy?": "",
  "Droughts are caused by excessive hydroelectric dam construction": "",
  "Hydroelectric power is not truly a renewable resource": "",
  "Fossil fuels are always more reliable than renewable energy": "",
  "The importance of having a diversified energy portfolio rather than relying heavily on a single source": "",
  "This scenario demonstrates why energy diversification is critical. Over-reliance on any single energy source, even a renewable one, creates vulnerability to disruptions. A diversified mix of solar, wind, hydro, and other sources provides greater resilience against weather-related and seasonal fluctuations.": "",
  "A school district installs solar panels on the roofs of all its buildings and finds that electricity costs drop by 40% in the first year. However, the district notices that electricity bills are still highest in December and January. What is the most likely explanation?": "",
  "Shorter daylight hours and lower Sun angles in winter reduce solar energy production": "",
  "Students use more electricity in winter because classes are harder": "",
  "The solar panels are defective and need replacement": "",
  "Electricity rates are artificially raised by utility companies in winter": "",
  "In the Northern Hemisphere, December and January have the shortest days and the lowest Sun angles, which significantly reduces the amount of solar energy reaching the panels. This means solar panels generate less electricity in winter, requiring the school to purchase more power from the grid.": "",
  "An island nation currently generates all its electricity from imported diesel fuel. Government officials propose transitioning to 100% renewable energy using a combination of solar, wind, and battery storage. What is the biggest engineering challenge they would face?": "",
  "Islands do not receive enough wind or sunlight for renewable energy": "",
  "Renewable energy sources produce too much electricity for a small island": "",
  "Solar panels and wind turbines cannot operate in tropical climates": "",
  "Ensuring reliable 24/7 power supply given the intermittent nature of solar and wind, requiring sufficient battery storage capacity": "",
  "The primary challenge for a 100% renewable energy system is ensuring reliable power around the clock despite the intermittent nature of solar and wind. This requires substantial battery storage capacity to store excess energy generated during peak production times and discharge it during low-production periods such as nighttime or calm weather.": "",
  "A farmer in Iowa has been approached by a wind energy company that wants to lease part of their land for wind turbines. The farmer can continue growing crops around the turbine bases. What is the term for this dual use of agricultural land for both farming and energy production?": "",
  "Monoculture energy": "",
  "Agrivoltaics or co-location": "",
  "Carbon farming": "",
  "Biofuel cropping": "",
  "The dual use of land for both agricultural production and energy generation is known as agrivoltaics (for solar) or co-location (for wind). Wind turbines occupy very small ground footprints, allowing farmers to continue cultivating crops or grazing livestock on the same land while earning additional income from energy leases.": "",
  "A state government offers tax credits to homeowners who install rooftop solar panels, and electricity rates from fossil fuel plants have been rising steadily. A family is calculating whether to invest $15,000 in a solar panel system that would save them $1,800 per year on electricity. Approximately how many years would it take for the system to pay for itself, not accounting for the tax credit?": "",
  "About 2 years": "",
  "About 20 years": "",
  "The system would never pay for itself": "",
  "About 8 years": "",
  "Dividing the $15,000 cost by the $1,800 annual savings gives approximately 8.3 years for the payback period. Since solar panels typically last 25-30 years, the family would enjoy roughly 17-22 years of essentially free electricity after the system pays for itself, making it a sound long-term investment.": ""
}